`crates/ctx-brief/src` is the ctx-brief binary crate: turns a `docs/STATUS.md` item or free-text ask into an executor-facing brief markdown file, driving Claude twice against a *target* repo (not this one) so that repo's own context hooks fire during gather and plan.

The pipeline is `main.rs` → `cli.rs` (parse argv, build `runner::Config`) → `runner.rs` (orchestrate) → `fs.rs`/`claude.rs` (trait seams) with `status_item.rs` resolving the backlog row. `error.rs`'s `BriefError` is the single error type threaded through all of these — every new failure mode gets a variant there, never a raw `io`/`anyhow` error. `contract.rs` is a documentation-drift guard: it must be kept in sync by hand whenever CLI flags, defaults, or the output-path convention change, since a battery check diffs it against generated docs.

Shared coupling: `cwd` is deliberately set to the *target* repo for both Claude invocations (`claude.rs`, `runner.rs`) — moving it breaks hook-triggered context loading, and this is stated in three places so don't "fix" it in only one. `runner::Config` carries two separate output-path variants (`out_rel` vs `out_fs`) that must not be conflated between the interactive session's write target and this process's own existence check. All filesystem access goes through the `Fs` trait (`fs.rs`) and all Claude calls through the `Claude` trait (`claude.rs`) — this is what makes `runner.rs` unit-testable without touching disk or shelling out; new runner logic needing either capability must go through these seams.

Output path derivation lives solely in `cli.rs`'s `slug()`/`to_config()` — changing it silently relocates where briefs land. `status_item.rs` shares its table/parser with `ctx-status` via `ctx_core::status_table`, so schema changes there ripple into both crates.